                content: "## The Inverse of Expansion\n\nFactorisation identifies shared attributes to simplify complex structures. Always re-expand to verify.\n\n## Diagram: Types of Factorisation\n\n| Type | Pattern | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Common Factor (HCF)** | $ab + ac = a(b + c)$ | $6x^2 + 9x = 3x(2x + 3)$ |\n| **Quadratic Trinomial** | $x^2 + bx + c = (x + p)(x + q)$ where $pq = c$ and $p + q = b$ | $x^2 + 7x + 10 = (x + 2)(x + 5)$ |\n| **Difference of Squares** | $a^2 - b^2 = (a - b)(a + b)$ | $x^2 - 16 = (x - 4)(x + 4)$ |\n\n## Diagram: Finding HCF \u2014 The Prime Breakdown\n\n| Term | Prime Factors |\n|---|---|\n| $6x^2$ | $2 \\\\times 3 \\\\times x \\\\times x$ |\n| $9x$ | $3 \\\\times 3 \\\\times x$ |\n| **HCF** | $3 \\\\times x = 3x$ |\n\n## Diagram: Finding LCM\n\n| Term | Prime Factors |\n|---|---|\n| $4x^2$ | $2^2 \\\\times x^2$ |\n| $6xy$ | $2 \\\\times 3 \\\\times x \\\\times y$ |\n| **LCM** | $2^2 \\\\times 3 \\\\times x^2 \\\\times y = 12x^2y$ |\n\n> **Rule**: HCF = take the **lowest** power of each common factor. LCM = take the **highest** power of every factor.\n\n## Diagram: Quadratic Factorisation Strategy\n\n| For $x^2 + bx + c$ | Find two numbers that... | Example: $x^2 + 7x + 10$ |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Multiply** to give $c$ | $p \\\\times q = c$ | $2 \\\\times 5 = 10$ \\\\checkmark |\n| **Add** to give $b$ | $p + q = b$ | $2 + 5 = 7$ \\\\checkmark |\n| **Answer** | $(x + p)(x + q)$ | $(x + 2)(x + 5)$ |\n\n## Practice Exercise\n\n1. Factorise $8p - 24$.\n2. Factorise $6y^2 + 12y$.\n3. Find the LCM of $3a^2b$ and $9ab^2$.\n4. Factorise $x^2 + 5x + 6$.\n5. Factorise $x^2 - 2x - 8$.",
